Motivation: (a) Briefly state the nature of your project and why you chose it. (b) State FOUR specific questions that you decided to explore for this dataset.

(a) I choose a COVID-19 dataset from Kaggle. On Kaggle page, this has more than one dataset. So I thought this can help me dive deep more about COVId-19. First dataset was perfect to see how COVID-19 has changed over past three month across countries. Secon dataset was great to see gender ratio, age ratio, and counts symtoms.

(b) First question: How the number of patients increased over time by country? At first I wanted to compare difference between countries, but after I turned my proposal, COVID-19 became worse around the world and caused more countries. So I decided to choose top four countries: Italy, China, U.S., and Korea. I will definitely show how they have changed over all countries, but for confirmed, death, active, and recover number, I will majory compare between those four countries.

Second question: Which gender and age range have highest number of patients? For this question, I wanted to see which gender showed highest percentage than other gender. Also, for age range, I created age rages first, such as 0-10,10-19, etc... Then, I divided them all ages to fall in each age ranges. I did this to see which age range are easily to get affected, because so many young people thought that they are free from this virus. I wanted to the truth with the number.

Third question: How is the degree of dispersion across the world? When I was talking about the degree of dispersion across the world, I wanted to show points on geographically how much they are dispersed. This will give idea of which continent or country is facing hard time than other continent or country. I will also show with different charts to show how they are dispersed.

Fourth questions: What kinds of symptoms they have before? I wanted to use NLTK for this to get which symptoms the patients have the most before they confirmed with COVID-19. I will count the words after I do cleanzing. Then, I will make a bar chart and word cloud to see which symptoms they had the most.

Data Source: Describe the dataset(s) you used, including the following minimal information:

  • the specific URL where the dataset or API resource was located (or provide a suitable sample)

I got this dataset from 'https://www.kaggle.com/sudalairajkumar/novel-corona-virus-2019-dataset'. I used two different dataset from this link: 'covid_19_data.csv' and 'COVID19_open_line_list'.

  • the data format and important variables and their types,

Datasets' format is in CSV file. For 'covid_19_data', ObservationDate -> When they got confirmed, Country/Region -> Which country they are from, Confirmed -> Confirmed cases in that date from that country, Deaths -> Death numbers per country per day, and Recovered-> Recovered number per day per country. For 'COVID19_open_line_list', age -> what age they are, sex -> which gender are they, latitude and longitude -> location where they got confirmed from, and symptoms -> what kinds of symptoms they had when they came to hospital.

  • how many records are included or retrieved (if using an API), and

For covid_19_data, it has 14811 rows. For COVID19_open_line_list, it has 13186 rows.

  • what time periods they covered (if there is a time element)

For covid_19_data, it covered until recently, April 13th, 2020. For COVID19_open_line_list, it covered until February 29th, 2020. To see compare numbers, I used the dataset that had recent confirmed cases, which is covid_19_data.

Methods: For each of the four questions, describe:

First question:

(a) how did you manipulate the data to prepare it for analysis?

I firstly grouped by date to compare confirmed, deaths, and recovered numbers of patients across the world. Then, I changed 'observationDate' to datetime. Then, I created active column by substracting Deaths number and Recovered number from Confirmed number. Next, I changed Mainland China to be all China in Country/Region column, so that I don't need to get two different values from China. Lastly, I duplicate Country/Region column to Country column in the same dataset. Then, I grouped by country to compare confirmed, deaths, and recovered numbers of patients across the world. I picked top 15 countries to show highest active, recovered, death cases. Also, I created mortality to calculate death rate out of confirmed cases.

(b) How did you handle missing, incomplete, or noisy data?

I tried to delete all rows that has NAs for all columns. Then, I deleted all NAs from each column that I tried to use for analysis. I dropped unnecessary column and changed name of column if necessary.

(c) How did you perform data analysis in code, i.e. Briefly describe the workflow of your source code

I used both bar chart and line chart to describe how the number has changed over time across the world. After I group the data by date, I create them as a new dataframe. Using new df, I tired to show the changes with data visualization.I showed them how the number have changed in differend types of cases over time. Then, I created new dataframe that grouped by country. I used this df to compare between countries how different types of cases have increased over time.

(d) What challenges did you encounter and how did you solve them?

When I decided to do this project, we had less number of countries that were affected by COVID-19. However, the number of countries has increased in a past few month. So, I had to choose only few countries that showed dynamic changes over time by COVID-19. Then, compare them to show how they have changed for different types of cases.

Second question:

(a) how did you manipulate the data to prepare it for analysis?

I had to choose COVID19_open_line_list.csv dataset to find gender ratio and age range percentage. First, I had to make changes on age column to make them in a several different ranges: 0-9,10-19,20-29,30-39,40-49,50-59...etc. In the age column, some ages were stated just as ages, while some others were stated as ranges. So I had to make them to be all in identical as age, then change them into age ranges. After that, I created visualization and dataframe to show ratios of age ranges and genders.

(b) How did you handle missing, incomplete, or noisy data?

I tried to delete all rows that has NAs for all columns. Then, I deleted all NAs from each column that I tried to use for analysis. For gender column, it was easy because I just need to change all answers to be female or male. However, for age column, each row had different types to state the age, so it was hard to make them to be in each age range. So, I had to change each answer to be changed and fall into each age range by coding and cleasing the column,

(c) How did you perform data analysis in code, i.e. Briefly describe the workflow of your source code

For gender, I used value_counts() to find how many female and male in this dataset. Then, I created a pie chart to show which gender has higher percentage than the other gender. For age column, I had to remove dash from this particular column and change type of age column from str to float by using .astype(float). Then, I calculate the age to be all 10th placed, such as 32 -> 30, 29 -> 20. Then I used replace to the values that were stated as ranged before to be all 10th placed, such as 2020 -> 20. Then I selected only 0.0 to 90.0 and change all these values to be one of age range (10.0 -> 10-19). I count each values using .value_counts() and caluclate percentage of each age range. Then I created new dataframe by using only these values. I created a pie chart to show visually this information. Lastly, I created a bar chart with average line in the middle to compare each age range.

(d) What challenges did you encounter and how did you solve them?

Only challenge that I faced was that the age column's answers were not very consistant. Some of them were written in age range, while some of them were written in age number.

Third question

(a) how did you manipulate the data to prepare it for analysis?

I choose 'covid_19_data.csv' for this analysis. I wanted to do a geographical analysis to show how the number of patients have spread out around the world. I found new csv file that has both latitude and lontitude from Kaggle. After I cleanzed my original data by changing name of country (ex: US to United States), I merged the original data and country (latitude and longitude) file on country name. Then, I used latitude and longitude as a plot on a map to see the dispersion. I used Confirmed cases to determine the size of circle. In this visualization, it shows the degree of dispersion. User can freely zoom in and out. Also, they can see exact number by clicking the circle.

(b) How did you handle missing, incomplete, or noisy data?

I dropped unnecessary column and rows. Then, I changed name of countries to get more countries to be merged by using country dataset, such as US to United States and UK to United Kingdom.

(c) How did you perform data analysis in code, i.e. Briefly describe the workflow of your source code

Firslt, I droped NAs from both columns. Then, I grouped my original data by country and add all confirmed cases by country. Next, I merge with country dataset that contains longitude and latitude with country name. Then, I only choose latitude, longitude, country naem, and confirmed cases to create new dataframe. With this new df, I created map by using folium.

(d) What challenges did you encounter and how did you solve them?

There was no challenge except for the size of circle. When I made it to be size as confirmed cases. It covered whole map. So I had to reduce the size by dividing with number (to keep ratio of circle size).

Fourth question

(a) how did you manipulate the data to prepare it for analysis?

For this question, I wanted to use NLP the most to determine which symptoms do patients have before they get confirmed with COVID-19. So, I downloade nltk words, stopwords, and punkt. Then, I used 'COVID19_open_line_list.csv' dataset to find it. I did some cleanse the column by using .replace() and drop any NAs in this column. Next, I change it to be string and remove number, stopwords, and do stemming.

(b) How did you handle missing, incomplete, or noisy data?

I dropped all NAs from the dataset and from symptoms column. Then, I replaced some unnecessary characters (including symbols).

(c) How did you perform data analysis in code, i.e. Briefly describe the workflow of your source code

After removing all unnecessaries, I counted the words. With this counted words, I created a bar chart and a word cloud show the number of counts to learn which symptoms the patients have.

(d) What challenges did you encounter and how did you solve them?

Only challenge that I had was that the some symptoms are two words or free text sentences. In those cases, it was not easy to make them as a word and remove unnecessaries.

country=data[data['Date']==data['Date'].max()].groupby(["country"]).agg({"Confirmed":'sum',"Recovered":'sum',"Deaths":'sum'}).sort_values(["Confirmed"],ascending=False)
country['Active'] = country['Confirmed'] - country['Deaths'] - country['Recovered']
country["Mortality"]=(country["Deaths"]/country["Confirmed"])*100
country["Recovery"]=round((country["Recovered"]/country["Confirmed"])*100,3)

I calculated mortality and recovery to compare ratio of deaths and recovered by country over time.

In [0]:
text = otherdata['symptoms'].to_string()
remove_digits = str.maketrans('', '', digits)
text = text.translate(remove_digits)
word_tokens = word_tokenize(text)
filtered_sentence = [w for w in word_tokens if not w in stop_words] 
filtered_sentence = [] 
for w in word_tokens: 
    if w not in stop_words: 
        filtered_sentence.append(w)
words = []
for w in filtered_sentence: 
    words.append(ps.stem(w))
